# NEXUS CRM — Cursor Coding Rules
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# READ THIS BEFORE WRITING ANY CODE
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## CORE RULE: NO INCOMPLETE CODE — EVER

You are building a production system. Every file you write must be:
- COMPLETE — no placeholders, no stubs, no "// implement later"
- WORKING — it must compile and run without changes
- CONNECTED — imports must resolve, types must match

## FORBIDDEN PATTERNS (never write these)

❌ // TODO
❌ // FIXME
❌ // implement this
❌ // add logic here
❌ throw new Error('Not implemented')
❌ return {} as any
❌ /* ... rest of implementation ... */
❌ // ... (abbreviated for brevity)
❌ // similar to above
❌ any type annotation (use unknown + type guard instead)
❌ Partial implementation with "you can add more later"

If you are about to write any of the above — STOP and write the real implementation instead.

## WHEN A FILE IS TOO LONG

If a file would exceed your output limit:
1. Write the first half completely
2. End with the comment: `// ── CONTINUE: next function is [functionName] ──`
3. Wait for the user to say "continue"
4. Write the second half completely from where you left off
5. Never summarize or abbreviate

## FILE WRITING RULES

- Write ONE complete file per response
- Always start with all imports at the top
- Always export everything that other files will need
- Always include error handling in every async function
- Always validate inputs with Zod before using them
- Always return the standard ApiResponse format: { success, data } or { success: false, error }
- Always add JSDoc comment to every exported function

## DATABASE RULES

- Every Prisma query must include `tenantId` in the where clause
- Always use the tenant isolation middleware — never bypass it
- Use transactions for any operation that writes to 2+ tables
- Never use `findUnique` without also checking the result is not null

## TYPESCRIPT RULES

- `strict: true` is enabled — respect it
- No implicit `any`
- Every function has explicit parameter types AND return type
- Use discriminated unions for state management
- Use `satisfies` operator for config objects

## FASTIFY ROUTE RULES

Every route handler must:
1. Parse and validate input with the Zod schema
2. Check permissions with `requirePermission()`
3. Call the service layer (no business logic in route handlers)
4. Return standard response format
5. Have try/catch that throws NexusError subclasses

## REFERENCE DOCUMENT

The full technical specification is in `NEXUS_CRM_Technical_Spec.md`.
- Prisma schemas: Section 31
- TypeScript types: Section 32
- Zod schemas: Section 33
- REST endpoints: Section 34
- Fastify bootstrap: Section 35
- RBAC: Section 35.2
- Kafka patterns: Section 36
- Build phases: Section 63

Always reference the spec. Do not invent schemas, types, or patterns.
